Predictiong term deposit subscribtion after telemarketing campaign

Abstract

In this report I would like to analyse banking telemarketing data and create models which predict whether particular client will subscribe a term deposit. In order to achieve that I will operate in accordance with CRISP-DM standard. Firstly I will try to understand the business processes in banking telemarketing and understand the provided data. Than 3 types of models will be created and assessed. I will skip implementation part as it is academic researc project.

Introduction

In general. There are two approaches to marketing campaigns: mass (traditional) marketing and direct marketing. The mass marketing uses media such as TV, radio or newspapers and direct marketing is performed via mail or phone (telemarketing) (Spiller, 2020). The problem of telemarketing is very important in some sectors of economy, especially in banking, where knowladge about customer needs is crucial (Asif, 2018). Increasing number of telemarketing and in general marketing campaigns has reduced their efficency. Moreover, the bad approach to client may result in negative feedback (Moro, Laureano, Cortez, 2011). On the other hand, proper clients targeting may reduce costs and time of the campaign, so proper prediction of client response is crucial. In this report I will focus on deposit clients and predict whether they will subscribe to term deposit.

Data describtion

Descriptive statistics

The data used in this report is derived from Portugese banking insitution telemarketing campaign. The data was colle from 2008 to 2013. In the dataset there are 20 input variables - 10 numeric and 10 cathegorical and output variable - y. The data consists of information about the client, a particular call or whole campaign, product and also about socio-economic situation in Portugal.

Summarising the data we can see the describtive statistics for numeric variables and counts of each cathegory for cathegorical ones. It is important to notice, that for some cathegorical variables there is response unknown. This response will have to be deleted and treated as missing value.

Y is target variable in this report. It is binary variable which describes whether the client has subscribed for a term deposit. From this plot we can see that the vast majority of clients has not subscribed for term deposit. It can cause issues as the sample is not balanced. However, those problems can be easily resolved by applying appriopriate threshold.

y_plot

Age and duration are both numeric variables. Age describes the age of client and duration describes the duration of last call in seconds. As it is not known prior to the call I will drop this variable from the dataeset, because it has none predictive value.

## Data preparation

Handling with missing data and outliers.

After exploring the data I concluded that the distribution of the data is irregular (as it can be seen on previous charts). So that outliers will not be removed from dataset as they can have some predictive value.

Firstly, I will handle with unknown values. The easiest way to do so is to read once again the data and define unknown as missing value. This way we will have appropriate factors in cathegorical variables.

data<-read.csv("bank-additional-full.csv",sep=";", na.strings = "unknown")

We can see from previous charts that value unknown was not that frequent and after replacement we do not have a problem of extensive missing data. In every variable missing data is below 25%. So it is preferable to impute the data rather than delete missing values or whole variable.Firstly, lets check pattern of missing valuse.

We can see that majority of data is nonmissing or is missing in only one variable (more than 96% of data). Also the chart does not seem to have any particular pattern. So we do rather have missing at random values.

aggr_plot <- aggr(data, col=c('cornflowerblue','indianred4'), numbers=TRUE, digits = 8, sortVars=TRUE, labels=names(data), cex.axis=.7, gap=3, ylab=c("Histogram of missing data","Pattern"))

Combining cathegories

As it was described during data exploration, some cathegories require to be combined. Firstly, to make distribution of education level more even I combined all basic levels and illiterate and created cathegory basic.

Moreover, I combined all white-collar jobs, and non-working cathegories (students, house maids, retired and unemployed). Also cathegories of enterprenour and self-employed has been joint. This way I reduced number of cathegories without losing a lot of information.

Also, in order to reduce number of cathegories months has been grouped by quarters of the year.

We can see that no in all cases it was posible to create even frequent cathegories, but surely the number of them was reduced, which will be helpful during one-hot encoding.

levels(completedData$education)[levels(completedData$education)%in%c("illiterate","basic.4y","basic.6y","basic.9y")] <- "basic"
summary(completedData$education)
##               basic professional.course         high.school   university.degree 
##               13229                5458                9911               12590
levels(completedData$job)[levels(completedData$job)%in%c("admin.","management","services","technician")] <- "white-collar"
levels(completedData$job)[levels(completedData$job)%in%c("entrepreneur","self-employed")] <- "entrepreneur/self-employed"
levels(completedData$job)[levels(completedData$job)%in%c("student","retired","housemaid","unemployed")] <- "not-working"

One hot encoding

In order to be able to use cathegorical data it is needed to perform one-hot encoding. To do so I changed every variable with n cathegories into n-1 variables. So if variable has 3 cathegories in the new data set there will be 1 more.The reference cathegories was chosen on basis of frequency (most frequent ones) or the order (most basic ones as in education or the oldest one as in day of week).

Numerical variables - density

In this paragraph I create histogram of each standardized numerical variables with density estimation.

OptimizeMfrow <- function(elements) {
  columns <- ceiling(sqrt(elements))
  rows <- ifelse(columns * (columns - 1) < elements, columns, columns - 1)
  return(c(rows, columns))
}



DoHistogram <- function(values, values.name) {
  histogram <- hist(values, plot = FALSE)
  density.estimate <- density(values)
  y.maximum <- max(histogram$density, density.estimate$y)
  plot(histogram, freq = FALSE, ylim = c(0, y.maximum), 
       xlab = values.name, ylab = "density", main = NULL)
  lines(density.estimate, lwd = 2, col="indianred4")
}

Modeling

Splitting the data

In order to properly evaluate the model I splitted data into 3 parts: training, validation and testing. On training which consists of 70% of data each model will be trained and validated on validation set (15%) to check if model is not over fitted. To choose the best model I will use test set (also 15% of data).

set.seed(77406)

SplitDataSet <- function(data.set, training.fraction, test.fraction){
  random.numbers <- sample.int(nrow(data.set))
  quantiles <- quantile(random.numbers, probs = c(0, test.fraction, training.fraction, 1))
  split.labels <- cut(random.numbers, quantiles, include.lowest = T,
                      labels = c("test", "training", "validation"))
  return(split(data.set, split.labels))
}

set <- SplitDataSet(newdata,0.85,0.15)
training <- set$training
test <- set$test
validation <- set$validation

Stepwise logistic regression

I created 3 stepwise regression. One backwards, one forwards and one in both ways. Each of these methods have selected the same variables.

full_model <- glm(yyes ~., data = training, family = "binomial")

zero_model <- glm(yyes ~1, data = training, family = "binomial")

back_model <- stepAIC(full_model, direction = "backward",trace = FALSE)
both_model <- stepAIC(zero_model,scope=list(lower=formula(zero_model),upper=formula(full_model)), direction="both", trace = FALSE)
for_model <- stepAIC(zero_model,scope=list(lower=formula(zero_model),upper=formula(full_model)), direction="forward", trace = FALSE)

As it is classification problem I decided to find optimal cutoffpoint. In this case opitmal cut off is equal 0.47 however we see that for training data it is on lower level.

CalculateCost <-function(cut.off, cost.matrix, score, true.y){
  prediction <- ifelse(score > cut.off, 1, 0)
  confusion.matrix <- prop.table(table(factor(prediction, levels = c(0, 1)),
                                       true.y))
  return(sum(cost.matrix * confusion.matrix))
}

cutoffs <- seq(0, 1, by = 0.01)
costmatrix <- matrix(c(0, 1, 1, 0), 2)

score <- costs <- list()

score[[1]] <- validation1$predictions
costs[[1]] <- sapply(cutoffs, CalculateCost, cost.matrix = costmatrix,
                     score = score[[1]], true.y = validation1$yyes)

score[[2]] <- training1$predictions
costs[[2]] <- sapply(cutoffs, CalculateCost, cost.matrix = costmatrix,
                     score = score[[2]], true.y = training1$yyes)


plot(data.frame(cutoffs, 0.7), type = "l", lty = 3, log = "y",
     ylim = range(c(0.7, unlist(costs))),
     ylab = "Cost per client", xlab = "Cut-off")
for (i in 1:2) {
  lines(cutoffs, costs[[i]], lty = i, lwd = 2)

### Neural network

To create best neural network I created 100 of them with diffrent weight decay parameter. Next I have chosen the best neural network - the one that minimises error on validation set.

neurons <- 5
decays <- seq(0, 40, length.out = 40)
wts_param <-  2 * runif(neurons * ncol(newdata) + neurons + 1) - 1
train.error <- valid_error <- numeric(length(decays))
NNs <- list()
AUC_v <- numeric(length(decays))

for (d in 1:length(decays)){
  NNs[[d]] <- nnet(yyes ~ ., data = training, size = neurons,
                           decay = decays[d], linout = T, maxit = 10000,
                           trace = FALSE, Wts = wts_param)
  prediction <- predict(NNs[[d]], newdata = validation)
  AUC_v[d] <- performance(prediction(prediction, validation$yyes),"auc")@y.values[[1]]
 
}


best_NN <- NNs[[which.max(AUC_v)]]

As it was done previously with other models, the best Neural Network will be validated based on predictions on both validation and training sets. AUC is equal to 0.94 on Validation set, which is very good result.
